'''Junkanburo''' (循環風呂) is one method of {{ill|Hot spring|ja|温泉|1=Onsen|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hot spring|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen|qq=}} {{ill|Hot water supply facility|ja|給湯設備|lt=hot water supply|lt_ja=給湯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hot water supply facility|qq=}} / {{ill|Drainage facility|ja|排水設備|lt=drainage|lt_ja=排水|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Drainage facility|qq=}} to the {{ill|Bath|ja|風呂|lt=bathtub|lt_ja=浴槽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bath|qq=}}. Natural or mechanically pumped {{ill|Source spring|ja|源泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Source spring|qq=}} water is supplied to the bathtub, and the overflow is collected into an overflow tank (pit). The water is then recirculated, undergoing {{ill|Filtration|ja|ろ過|lt=filtration|lt_ja=濾過|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Filtration|qq=}}, and mixed with a {{ill|Chlorine|ja|塩素|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chlorine|qq=}}-based {{ill|Disinfectant|ja|消毒薬|lt=chemicals|lt_ja=薬剤|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Disinfectant|qq=}} before returning again to the {{ill|Bath|ja|風呂|lt=bathtub|lt_ja=浴槽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bath|qq=}}. It contrasts with {{ill|Kakenagashi (continuous flow)|ja|掛け流し|1=Kakenagashi|2=ja|3=掛け流し|4=zh|5=掛け流し|lt=Kakenagashi (flowing baths)|6=de|7=Kakenagashi|8=fr|9=Kakenagashi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kakenagashi (continuous flow)|13=User:Immanuelle/Kakenagashi|qq=}}. This recirculation system is commonly used in facilities such as {{ill|Day-trip bathing facility|ja|日帰り入浴施設|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Day-trip bathing facility|qq=}}.
== How to Distinguish Junkanburo from Kakenagashi == * Facility layouts vary, so there is no absolute rule, but the following points can be helpful: ** If water is constantly being drawn from a drain at the bottom of the tub, and if the supply of water is not causing any noticeable overflow, it is likely to be a Junkanburo system. ** Even if there is overflow, if it flows randomly over the entire tub edge, it is generally Kakenagashi; however, if it overflows only at a specific location (a recessed edge of the bathtub), where water from outside the bathtub (washing area water, rainwater, water from other tubs, etc.) does not enter, it may still be a recirculating system. ** In open-air baths with a roof designed to exclude rain, there is a higher likelihood of a Junkanburo system. ** If a strong chlorine smell is present, this also indicates a Junkanburo. ** Although there are regional differences, in many Junkanburo setups, the hot water is always supplied from inside the tub itself. ** In an area not known for abundant volcanic springs—especially a busy hot-spring town with many hotels and ryokan close together—large communal baths accommodating around 100 people are usually Junkanburo.
== Advantages of Junkanburo == * By filtering and recirculating, operators can conserve spring water and reduce costs such as sewage fees. ** Note that in the case of true Kakenagashi (continuous flow) from a natural source, the used water may be treated as rainwater, so sewage fees do not apply. * Helps prevent depletion of the spring source. * Makes it easier to maintain hygiene standards, especially when handling large numbers of bathers.
== Disadvantages of Junkanburo == * To prevent the proliferation of {{ill|Legionella|ja|レジオネラ菌|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Legionella|qq=}}, chlorine-based chemicals must be used, maintaining a prescribed level of residual chlorine during filtration cycles. ** This filtration process can also remove beneficial mineral components inherent in the hot spring. * When chlorine-based agents are used, any added pigments (for seasonal “themed” baths, etc.) become ineffective. ** The distinctive aroma of natural hot spring water is often masked by the smell of chlorine chemicals.
== References == * 温泉教授の温泉ゼミナール (Kobunsha Shinsho) * これは、温泉ではない (Kobunsha Shinsho)
== External Links == * [http://www.city.yokohama.lg.jp/kenko/eiken/life-inf/mizu/24bath.html Yokohama City Institute of Health: "I’m using a 24-hour bath, but..."]
